Don't add the `maintainer-merge` label by hand! That's the safest way for your PR to go through the cracks.

> Don't add the `maintainer-merge` label by hand! That's the safest way for your PR to go through the cracks.

Perhaps I don't understand the control flow here, but that label was added earlier by @Ruben-VandeVelde, and I was restoring it. I think I have responded to comments adequately, and would like to avoid further delays.

The control flow is that, when someone `maintainer merge`s a PR, the bot sends a message to a private stream. Then either a maintainer merges the PR or a reviewer points something out. In either case, they react to the bot's message with an emoji to indicate that no more attention is needed.

By changing the label by hand, you're taking off the PR from the queue _without_ the bot sending a message to the private stream. In short, you're making your PR invisible.

I find it a bit hard to parse `f '' (s \ t) = f '' s \ f '' (s ∩ t)` optically.
I know that redundant parentheses are unpopular, but I personally would like to see 
`f '' (s \ t) = (f '' s) \ (f '' (s ∩ t))` here.

```suggestion
lemma InjOn.image_diff_of_subset {f : α → β} {t : Set α} (h : InjOn f s) (hst : t ⊆ s) :
```

```suggestion
  fun ⟨x, hx⟩ ⟨y, hy⟩ h' ↦ by simpa [imageFactorization, h.eq_iff hx hy] using h'
```
These two theorems should have invFunOn in the name rather than invFun, I think

```suggestion
  refine subset_antisymm (subset_diff.2 ⟨image_subset f (diff_subset s t), ?_⟩)
```

Can you first prove the following lemma?
```suggestion
lemma InjOn.image (h : s.InjOn f) (h₁ : s₁ ⊆ s) (h₂ : s₂ ⊆ s) :
    s.Powerset.InjOn (image f) :=
  fun s₁ hs₁ s₂ hs₂ h' ↦ by rw [← h.preimage_image_inter h₁, h', h.preimage_image_inter h₂]
```

```suggestion
```
Is this an iff?
Maybe, but applying this in the other direction feels contrived to me.
Please avoid creating consensus by resolving review comments you didn't address. Maintainers can always decide whether those comments are worth discarding.

> Maybe, but applying this in the other direction feels contrived to me. 

Iffs do not necessarily need to be applied the other way to be useful. A great use of them is rewriting.
You lose dot notation this way. Adding a separate `iff` lemma is possible, but it feels almost useless to me.
Two lemmas sounds like the way to go to me

```suggestion
    (hrt : r ⊆ t) : f '' f.invFunOn s '' r = r :=
```
Why are you keeping the brackets?

```suggestion
    f '' f.invFunOn s '' t = t :=
```
Same here

This is the lemma I would call `image_diff`
```suggestion
lemma InjOn.image_diff {f : α → β} {t : Set α} (h : InjOn f s) (hst : t ⊆ s) :
```
What about `image_diff_subset`?

and this is the lemma I would consider "auxiliary"
```suggestion
lemma InjOn.image_diff' {t : Set α} (h : s.InjOn f) : f '' (s \ t) = f '' s \ f '' (s ∩ t) := by
```
I disagree.
You're missing the `ssubset` lemma
Do we have the `subset_left` version? If not, can you add it?

There should be a `of` somewhere
```suggestion
theorem SurjOn.image_invFunOn_image_of_subset [Nonempty α] {r : Set β} (hf : SurjOn f s t)
```

I was going to say that those lemmas should be replaced by `RightInvOn` statements as this is what the API expects you to use and I was going to suggest you the proofs. But I see you already found the proofs so you might as well drop the lemmas. We don't want one lemma of the form `f '' g '' s = s` for every possible pair of functions `f` and `g` that are inverse to each other on some set `s`. These lemmas are easily accessed on the fly using the API.
Easily accessed only once you know they're there. I think this special case is prominent enough for these lemmas to exist so they're easily findable.
Will let someone else weigh in

Of course the lemmas are already there at the right generality, for me it is about the analogy between `InjOn` and `SurjOn`. It feels counterintuitive that for one, certain lemmas are there, but for others the lemmas that look like they should be there actually aren't. I think that it's best not to require that people figure out the reason for this. 

I'm also not sure how far through the API `exact?` can see in this case, but possibly this helps with that as well.

```suggestion
lemma InjOn.image_diff_of_subset {f : α → β} {t : Set α} (h : InjOn f s) (hst : t ⊆ s) :
```
@apnelson1 I think you missed this comment?
for these and the next two lemmas, it's probably unambiguous to remove `_of_subset`?
possibly even use `image_inj` instead of `image_eq_image`
